# Week 10 - Day 3
## Sliding Window Maximum (LeetCode 239)

### 🧠 Problem Statement
Given an array of integers `nums` and an integer `k`, 
there is a sliding window of size `k` moving from left to right.
Return the maximum value in each window.

### 🔍 Example
Input:
nums = [1,3,-1,-3,5,3,6,7]
k = 3

Output:
[3,3,5,5,6,7]

---

## 💡 Approach

We use a **Monotonic Deque (Decreasing Order)**:

- Store indices in deque.
- Front always stores index of maximum element.
- Remove:
  - Elements out of window.
  - Smaller elements from back.

---

## ⚙️ Algorithm

1. Process first `k` elements.
2. For each new element:
   - Add previous window max to answer.
   - Remove elements outside window.
   - Remove smaller elements.
   - Insert current index.
3. Add max of last window.

---

## ⏱ Time Complexity
O(n)

Each element is pushed and popped at most once.

## 🗃 Space Complexity
O(k)

---

## 🏷 Topics Covered
- Sliding Window
- Deque
- Monotonic Queue
- Optimization from O(nk) → O(n)class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> maxSlidingWindow(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n=nums.size();
        vector<int> ans;
        deque<int> dq;
      for(int i=0;i<k;i++){
        while(dq.size()>0 && nums[dq.back()]<=nums[i]){
            dq.pop_back();
        }
        dq.push_back(i);
      }

      for(int i=k;i<n;i++){
        ans.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
        // removing values those are not the part of current window
        while(dq.size()>0 && dq.front()<=i-k){
            dq.pop_front();
        } 
        
        // removing the smaller vales
        while(dq.size()>0 && nums[dq.back()]<=nums[i]){
        dq.pop_back();
        }
        dq.push_back(i);
      }
      ans.push_back(nums[dq.front()]);
      return ans;
    }
};
